In article <1992Jan9.041126.26502@qualcomm.com> karn@chicago.qualcomm.com writes:
>After doing a DES myself, I tend to support
>the theory that says it was deliberately designed to make it as slow
>as possible in software.
>
>The only way to make DES go fast in software is to throw megabytes of
>memory at it for precomputed lookup tables. (See Dave Feldmeier's
>paper on this subject in Crypto '89).  
>
>Phil

Hmmm.  I can do DES CBC en/decryption at 350 K bytes/second on an SGI 4D/480
workstation (on a single CPU).  I use less than 3k bytes of tables.
Does that not qualify as a "way to make DES go fast in software"?
